body:
The SystemVerilog language supports Assertion control system tasks (IEEE 1800-2023 20.11). Such tasks are not supported by the Verilator.

This PR provides partial support for the parameterless assertion control tasks. The following new tasks were introduced:
- `$assertoff` - disables assertions in the current module and its submodules,
- `$asserton` - enables assertions in the current module and its submodules,
- `$assertkill` - alias for `$assertoff`, due to Verilator assertion design there is no need distinguishing them.

Assertion control tasks are supported inside modules and user-defined free functions. When assertion control is defined inside function it is propagated in the same way as if it was inlined. There is no implemented support for assertion controls inside classes.

`$assertoff` statements have the following form in the generated simulation code:

<strike>

```cpp
constexpr std::array<const char*, 2> t_multiple_assertctls12_assertions = {
        "t.multiple_assertctls",
        "t.nested_multiple_assertctls.multiple_assertctls",
    };
    for (const char* name : t_multiple_assertctls12_assertions) {
           vlSymsp->_vm_contextp__->assertOnFor(name, false);
    }
```
</strike>

```cpp
    if (vlSymsp->_vm_contextp__->assertOn()) {
        if (VL_UNLIKELY((1U & (~ (IData)(vlSelf->t__DOT__clk_module_with_assert__DOT____Vassert_port))))) {
            VL_WRITEF_NX("[%0t] %%Error: t_assert_ctl_immediate_bad.v:59: Assertion failed in %Nt.clk_module_with_assert: 'assert' failed.\n",0,
                         64,VL_TIME_UNITED_Q(1),-12,
                         vlSymsp->name());
            VL_STOP_MT("t/t_assert_ctl_immediate_bad.v", 59, "");
        }
    }
```
 <strike>

For each control statement, affected assertion scopes are aggregated (using Graph generated in V3Assert) and then for each scope, status of assertion is updated accordingly. Then each assertion is wrapped around by:
```cpp
 if (VL_UNLIKELY(vlSymsp->_vm_contextp__->assertOnFor("t.nested_multiple_assert_instances.module_with_assert1"))) {
        ...
    }
```

This ensures that the assertion is enabled and should be run.

</strike>

Since the SystemVerilog standard allows runtime assertion control evaluation (ex. under non-const if block) each assertion status change need to be performed during simulation run. However, for each assertion which is not affected by the assertion control statement, behavior remains unchanged. This does not apply for multiple-instances scenario, where if before any instance declaration assertion control is used, all assertions would perform additional assert-status lookup.
